The Evolution of Sequencing Technology: A half-century of progress

talk title: Development of capillary electrophoresis technology

speaker: Norman Dovichi

date: July 16-19 2015

<https://library.cshl.edu/Meetings/sequencing/video-pages/Dovichi.php>

LLM summary: Norman Dovichi chronicles the evolution of capillary electrophoresis (CE) for high-throughput DNA sequencing, originating from his postdoc work at Los Alamos on sheath-flow cuvettes enabling attogram- and zeptomole-level laser-induced fluorescence (LIF) detection—pioneering single-molecule sensitivity. Integrating this with Jorgenson's CE for automated, efficient separations, he addressed slab-gel limitations in early dye-labeled automated sequencers (e.g., Lloyd Smith's primer dyes, Ansorge's slab fluorescence, Prober's terminator dyes). In 1988, he sketched a multi-capillary array instrument, DOE-funded despite initial rejections, yielding a 16/32-capillary system with chopper-multiplexed argon/YAG lasers imaging to photodiode arrays. Pivotal separations shifted from unstable cross-linked polyacrylamide to linear polyacrylamide, countering bias reptation—a field-dependent entanglement transition limiting read lengths—via modest fields (<300 V/cm) and elevated temperatures (>60°C), which serendipitously extended the Ogston-to-reptation transition (N*) while resolving compressions from secondary structure, achieving ~600-base four-color Sanger reads on M13mp18 and GC-rich bacterial genes, including the first CE-generated GenBank entries in 1997.


