# Introduction

It's a pleasure to be here. It's an honor to be here. Thank you very much for the opportunity.

I'm going to talk about development of capillary electrophoresis for DNA sequencing. I'll begin showing you some data technology that was developed before the beginning of the genome project, and we've had a good introduction to it. I'm going to take a slightly different tack on this.

# Postdoctoral Work at Los Alamos

I had done my postdoctoral fellowship at Los Alamos Scientific Laboratory in Dick Keller's lab. And Dick's a physical chemist and I was there to do physical chemistry.

Through a series of happy accidents I spent half of my time in a biophysics group doing flow cytometry. And we investigated flow cytometry as a tool for ultra sensitive detection.

In flow cytometry, samples introduced into the center of a square optically flat flow chamber. Sheath fluid surrounds the analyte and draws it out as a thin filament which passes through the laser beam, fluorescence excited, filtered and sent to detector. We investigated that.

# Ultrasensitive Detection in Sheath-Flow Cuvettes

I moved and took an independent position at the University of Wyoming. And when I was there, I and my colleagues at Los Alamos wrote a paper which we published in Science which described attogram detection limits for aqueous dye samples.

And what we demonstrated is this sheath flow cuvette, laser-induced fluorescence combination, provides exquisite sensitivity. And at the bottom there we have on average only half a Rhodamine 6G molecule was present in the 6 picoliter probe volume. And this was the genesis of all single molecule detections.

We have a second follow-up paper which articulated how to achieve single molecule detection. And it represented a couple of order of magnitude improvement detection limits compared to alternatives.

And so this technology based on the sheath flow cuvette provides extremely high sensitivity, extremely wide dynamic range, but it requires small samples, picoliter to nanoliter volume samples. And it provides no information as to the identity of the analyte other than the fluorescent signature.

# Introduction to Capillary Zone Electrophoresis

Later that year, Jim Jorgenson published his review article on capillary zone electrophoresis. Jim and I were undergraduates together at Northern Illinois University and followed each other's work fairly closely.

In this particular paper, Jim points out that capillary electrophoresis provides an approach to automating, instrumentizing, as he put it, electrophoresis. Because conventional electrophoresis because of the gel is not easy to adapt it to online sample applications detection quantification or automated operation. So modern electrophoresis, powerful, but not automated.

In capillary electrophoresis, a fused silica capillary is looped between two sample reservoirs. High voltage is applied, a sample is injected into the capillary and analytes separated across the capillary.

Capillaries are made out of fused silica. I brought a capillary with me. Here is one capillary. You can't see it. If I had two capillaries, they would look like this. Here, you can pass it around for your amusement.

These things cost about a buck a meter. The reason why we use 150 micrometer outer diameter capillary is because that's the cheapest capillary that we could purchase.

The high surface-to-volume ratio of the capillary allows efficient radiation of heat and application and use of high voltages. These capillaries are flexible. You can tie that thing in a knot. Can support high electric fields, which leads to fast and efficient separations.

They use ridiculously small sample volumes, nanoliter injection volumes, but they require sensitive detection, picomolar better.

# Combining CE with LIF Detection

So it seems reasonable then to combine the two technologies. In, when was it? I guess it was in 88, Yongfeng Cheng, who moved with me from the University of Wyoming to the University of Alberta, where all of the subsequent work was done, coupled capillary electrophoresis to laser-induced fluorescence in the sheath flow cuvette, and we studied fluorescein isothiocyanate labeled amino acids as an approach to high-sensitivity protein sequencing, which went nowhere.

But we achieved detection limits down in what we now called the zeptomole range. We rapidly improve this down to single molecule detection.

The combination of the techniques then provides fast and efficient separations so you know what your analyte is and then also provides the optimal detection limit, essentially infinite sensitivity.

# Pre-Genome Automated Slab-Gel Sequencers

Now, a second bit of pre-genome instrumentation was reviewed by Lloyd and Leroy, and that's the automated DNA sequencers. I'll highlight three papers.

The first, of course, is their Nature paper which used dye-labeled primers. A second paper was published by Ansorge which used fluorescent dye, single fluorescent dye, and essentially replaced the radioactive label with a fluorescent label in classic slab gel electrophoresis.

I was not aware of those two papers when they were published I did not subscribe to either of those journals I did subscribe to Science and when Prober paper came out with dye-labeled terminators I became very interested very excited.

So the first technology was commercialized by ABI the second one by Pharmacia, and the third one briefly by DuPont. And these technologies replace the radioactive label with fluorescence detection. It eliminates autoradiography and an automated sequence calling, extremely powerful tools for DNA analysis.

They use, though, slab gels, and slab gels cannot support high electric fields. They provide slow separations. Gel preparation is tedious, and sample loading is manual.

# Conception of Multi-Capillary Array Instrument

And then finally, I recognize all of this, put it together, and flying to Boston on November 1st, 1988, this is something I never do. I jotted down an idea, and I saved the piece of paper. and scanned this a couple of days ago.

And I designed a multiple capillary, a capillary array electrophoresis instrument. And then the idea was we would take our sheath flow cuvette and instead of using a square flow chamber, we'd use a rectangular flow chamber.

We'd take an array of capillaries, sort of like the teeth on a comb, and put them inside of that rectangular flow chamber. Sheath flow would then surround the capillaries, draw analyte out as thin filaments, excite with a single laser beam, collect fluorescence at the side, and image onto a camera of some sort.

We didn't have funding for that. But later the next year, the following notice appeared in Chemical and Engineering News that the Department of Energy was going to start developing technology for the Human Genome Initiative.

And one of the topics they were interested in was the development of innovative and cost-effective technologies, leading to rapid and accurate large-scale sequencing.

# Instrument Development and Funding

So now I'm going to describe the capillary electrophoresis instrumentation and then the separation technology. For the instrumentation, we obtained funding from DOE, developed a capillary array electrophoresis instrument based on that original design.

Here are 32 capillaries sitting inside of a rectangular chamber. The capillaries flow from the top or pass through the top into the center of the chamber. The capillaries are arrayed linearly, sheath buffers pumped in, flows out the bottom.

Here's operation for 16 capillaries. Laser beam skims beneath the tip of the capillaries. Analyte flows off the capillaries, focused into the laser beam fluorescence is collected and imaged Photograph or diagram of the instrument

# Detection System Details

We use the green laser that this laser the frequency doubled neodymium YAG also the argon ion laser. We'd use the two lasers because we were using ABI's dye set. Chopper will alternate, excite the two fluorescent dyes.

Beams are combined at a dichroic beam splitter, focused with an objective into the cuvette, collected, passed through the same filter wheel that Lloyd used and just described, image onto a array of gradient index lens coupled optical fibers, to have large photodiodes.

We had the photodiodes at minus 20 degrees Celsius. This was Edmonton in winter, so we heated the detectors to minus 20, because outside it was minus 30 to minus 40 when we were doing these experiments.

A photograph of the instrument in operation, two laser beams, chopped dichroic filter, and sent on to the instrument, or to the cuvette.

