# Early Sequencing Data

We used M13mp18 a lot as our test system, and here is data off of that 16 capillary instrument. Here's the penta-T quartet-T in the M13 sequence at about 325 nucleotides, and you see exquisite reproducibility from capillary to capillary.

# Parallel Development by Hitachi and Commercialization

Simultaneously, in parallel and independently, Hitachi came up with exactly the same idea. The two patents or patents from the two groups were combined by Perkin-Elmer, which had Applied Biosystems at that time, developed the model 3700 DNA sequencer, blah, blah, blah.

The 3700 analyzer is designed for customers who require ultra-high throughput, 24-hour multi-run unattended automation and operating costs that meet the requirement of very large projects such as completion of the sequencing phase of the human genome. Cool.

# Separation Technology Challenges: Cross-Linked Polyacrylamide

There's a big step though between the hardware and the instrumentation and it has to do with its details and the separation. I'm going to spend the rest of my talk going through this.

In 1990, four groups jumped on the bandwagon of developing high throughput sequencers, or capillary electrophoresis as DNA sequencing tools. Four papers appeared in 1990.

First one was by Harold Swerdlow, who was a graduate student in Richard Gesteland's lab at Utah. one was out of Lloyd Smith's group. Lloyd tells me they were the first ones to submit on the manuscript.

Another two papers, one from Barry Karger and one from my group, appeared back-to-back issues of J. Chromatogr.

Swerdlow introduced himself to me at a conference, and we arranged for him to spend nine months at Alberta teaching us how to do DNA sequencing. We taught him details of capillary electrophoresis and laser-induced fluorescence. Remember this is Alberta. cold there, and so Swerdlow was a dedicated student to go up there.

All the early technologies used the same gel chemistry that was used in slab gels. This is cross-linked polyacrylamide.

As Harold pointed out in a paper, efforts to exploit this technology have been hampered by problems with the reproducibility and instability of gels. That's an understatement. You had to throw the gels away after one or two operations, which reduces the opportunity for automation.

# Breakthrough: Linear Polyacrylamide

This was pretty quickly identified by the community and there's a series of papers dealing with this issue, the use of linear polyacrylamide.

I highlight this paper from Boček's group in the Czech Republic, Czechoslovakia at that time, and they use non-cross-linked polyacrylamide. Linear polyacrylamide solution.

These things have the viscosity of syrup and can be pumped into the capillary. And as he says, or they say at the bottom, the time-consuming in-capillary polymerization step could be avoided and fast and reproducible repetition of the analysis was assured.

It's the key breakthrough that allowed the automation of capillary electrophoresis for DNA sequencing.

Here's some M13 data again. This is a T-terminated ladder. You'll see the classic exponential decrease in peak amplitude as you go later in the run, which is a hallmark of the Sanger sequencing reaction.

I'll highlight the penta-T, quartet-T, and you see the beautifully uniformly spaced peaks. This non-cross-linked acrylamide works beautifully for these short fragments.

# Bias-Reptation Phenomenon

Unfortunately, for large fragments, you see this big blob at the end of the run. And this big blob is associated with a phenomenon called bias-reptation.

And we worked a lot with Gary Slater at the University of Ottawa and Jean-Louis Viovy at the Institute Curie to begin to understand this phenomenon to characterize it.

And what you observe if you plot migration time versus fragment length is a region where you operate under Ogston separation mechanism where the DNA takes on a random coil configuration.

Later in the run this reptation phenomenon occurs where the DNA becomes stretched out in a line and moves through the gel as a snake crawls through grass. This leads to a co-migration, where all of these fragments above a certain threshold have the same migration time and cannot be resolved.

So this reptation becomes more important at high fields. So we're interested in high fields to speed up the separation.

# Electric Field Trade-Offs

At 100 volts per centimeter, we see a four-hour separation. At 250 volts per centimeter, we're down to an hour-long separation. At 300 volts per centimeter, we're under an hour for the separation.

Unfortunately, reptation is worse at high fields and the read length drops. So there's a trade-off between the electric field that one uses and the read length that you obtain.

This is described by a parameter called N*, which is the onset of bias reptation and where reptation becomes devastating. At low electric fields, you can get good separations out to very large fragments, but as you increase the electric field to 300 volts per centimeter, the fragment lengths drop.

So it's a trade-off between fragment length and speed.

# Temperature Effects on Separations

Simultaneously and independently, we were looking at heating to relax compressions. Here's the compressions in the M13 sequence at the bottom. Peaks are jumbled at the top at 60 degrees Celsius. The peaks are uniformly spaced.

Fortuitously, we observed that heating relaxes reptation for linear polyacrylamide, not for cross-linked, but for linear polyacrylamide. And what we observed is the big blob at the end of the run decreases as we increased temperature.

and we had the serendipitous and wonderful observation that N*, the onset of bias reptation, gets better and better for long, becomes longer and longer fragments the higher temperature you run.

So we have a wonderful situation where higher temperature provides faster separations and allows longer read length.

We summarized this in our paper in 95. To obtain long read lengths, it is necessary to operate capillaries in modest electric fields. to obtain data that's free of compression and relaxed bias reptation necessary to operate the capillary at elevated temperature and to make an automated instrument is necessary to use non polyacrylamide.

# Four-Color Sequencing Achievements

We did this used it demonstrated four color sequencing on M13 Here the first 320 bases There the penta-T quartet-T And then we were able to call the sequence reasonably well out to about 600 bases in a couple of hour operation.

# Real-World Applications

We not only worked with M13, we worked with a number of real samples. We were affiliated with the Canadian Bacterial Diseases Network. We worked with Roger Levesque to look at some Pseudomonas sequences. Those are very GC-rich fragments, terribly compression-ridden. And that led to the development of the high temperature.

And we also worked with Tony Chow who is interested in using heat shock protein as a marker for species identification of bacteria.

We submitted this particular set of data. When did we submit this? In, in, in, in. Yeah, there it is, March 11, 1997. And that was the first data in GenBank generated using capillary electrophoresis.

We ended up doing a dozen different species or sequencing this heat shock protein off of a dozen different species.

