# Q&A: Reptation vs. Compressions

Hello. I think you used your term. Is it reptation and compression interchangeably?

Of course, Sanger described compression, and he thought that was due to local secondary structure in the DNA that he was separating on his gels. And that's why I think he decided to raise the temperature. But it wasn't well defined on gels. But we all knew that you had to run your gels hot if you wanted to avoid these compressions. You are absolutely correct.

I conflated the two in my talk because of time. And compressions, indeed, are a result of secondary structure. The reptation, and I guess you can describe it as a secondary structure, but it's independent of sequence and is a different phenomenon.

And we were well aware that gels were classically run at high temperatures. When you try to do gels, the cross-linked gels at high temperature, you have the unfortunate situation that read length drops. So this N* parameter, the onset of bias reptation gets worse and dramatically worse when you raise temperatures.

And the concern with the non-cross-linked polyacrylamide is the material would elute from the column, pump out of the column because its viscosity would drop.

And we though were forced to do this because these ugly samples that Roger Levesque gave us were unsequenceable without relaxing the compressions, without relaxing, yeah, secondary structure.

So when I talk to students about this project, I point out that you can't just use standard materials because we were really good at doing M13. We were so good we didn't have to load a sample and we could call the sequence, right? But you have to work with real samples because the real samples will reveal the limitations of the technology. and that leads to the improvements that work.

Thank you for explaining it to me. Other comments?

# Q&A: Temperature and Band Broadening

I was just curious about how you disentangle temperature effects and the electrophoretic mechanism, in other words, reptation versus temperature broadening. Because temperature broadening will also cause loss of resolution.

So Lloyd is referring to a subtle aspect of capillary electrophoresis. In capillary electrophoresis the driving force is uniform across the diameter cross of the capillary which gives rise to a flat flow profile Anything that distorts this flat flow profile is going to lead to band broadening So you don't want any pressure flow which will give you a parabolic flow profile

If you have a temperature gradient across the diameter of the capillary, that temperature gradient leads to a viscosity gradient, which leads to a velocity gradient, which leads to peak broadening.

We were pretty obsessive in keeping our electric fields under control so that we were not generating a significant amount of joule heating in the capillaries. So a routine would be to generate an ohms plot, measuring current versus voltage, and make sure that we were well within the linear range.

And one of the beauties or fortuitous aspects of working with the non-crosslinked acrylamide is that it didn't work well at high temperatures, or rather high voltages, and we worked below 300 volts per centimeter,

Whereas the cross-link material, we operated up at 1,000 volts per centimeter. You get these ridiculously short separations, five minutes, and you get 200 bases of sequence. But at any rate, so we operated under conditions to minimize the band broadening associated with the temperature profile.

Any other comments?

## Intuitions

- **Sheath-flow cuvette LIF**: Core to ultrasensitive (attogram/zeptomole/single-molecule) detection via hydrodynamic focusing into thin filaments, wide dynamic range, but demands tiny volumes; genesis of all single-molecule fluorescence methods.
- **CE advantages**: Fused-silica capillaries enable high fields (fast/efficient separations, nL injections) due to superior heat dissipation vs. slab gels; automatable sans gels.
- **Multi-capillary array**: Parallelization via linear capillary comb in rectangular sheath-flow chamber, single laser excitation, side fluorescence imaging to photodiode array; chopper/dichroics for multi-wavelength (ABI dyes); led to ABI 3700.
- **Linear vs. cross-linked polyacrylamide**: Linear polymer solutions enable syringe-pump replacement (automation, reproducibility) vs. unstable/irreproducible in-capillary polymerization of cross-linked gels.
- **Bias reptation**: Mechanistic insight—Ogston (random coil sieving) transitions to reptation (chain reptates snake-like through pores) at N* fragments; field-accelerated (trade-off: speed vs. read length); sequence-independent co-migration "blob".
- **High-temperature trick**: Relaxes sequence-specific compressions (secondary structure) *and* serendipitously delays/extends N* in linear polyacrylamide (unlike cross-linked); faster diffusion aids disengagement, enabling ~600 nt reads at modest fields (<300 V/cm, >60°C).
- **Joule heating control**: Ohms plots ensure linear regime, minimizing radial temperature/viscosity gradients → parabolic flow → band broadening.
- **Real samples drive innovation**: M13 excels on standards but GC-rich Pseudomonas/heat-shock genes reveal compressions, forcing high-T solutions.

